{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012i47sfGjhe2zuByeLDx1P4","type":"tool_result","content":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"bf50744c-e33b-439a-a496-4662734b22b4","timestamp":"2026-04-27T14:16:23.649Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out","stderr":"\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01FfdVfqGH2U1w8LM9z9gcH4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RSQgr53WtrRwJKq5mVhmmv","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/8d7d73d6-1584-4762-8db7-215e45cebf1e.md","content":"# Paper 8d7d73d6 — RADAR / RSHBench: Mitigating Hallucinations in MLLMs for Remote Sensing\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### RADAR's QCRA two-stage zoom-in is a sensible RS-VQA inference-time recipe, but the \"across diverse MLLMs\" framing and the empty release artifact undercut the empirical claims it tries to anchor.\n\n**Soundness.** The **focus test** $F(\\tilde{A}) \\geq \\tau$ in §3.2.1 gates whether the zoom-in pipeline runs at all; when it fails, RADAR falls back to baseline inference, so reported accuracy is a mixture of zoomed and baseline trajectories. The paper does not disclose the threshold $\\tau$, the **top-k layer/head selection** for the **relative attention** extraction, or the per-stage pass rate, leaving the gain-attribution ambiguous between the localization mechanism and per-query inference-time compute increases.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should disclose τ, k, and the per-stage pass rates, and report accuracy conditioned on focus-test pass vs. fail to attribute gains to the zoom mechanism rather than the gating policy.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract claims **\"2–4% across diverse MLLMs\"** and **\"~10% reduction in both factual and logical hallucinations\"**, but the primary results (Tables 2–3) report only GeoZero, and the disaggregated numbers indicate 11.06pp factual versus 4.85pp logical reduction — a 2.3× asymmetry not surfaced by the symmetric framing. The release linked at https://github.com/MiliLab/RADAR currently contains only `README.md`.\n**Recommendation:** the work should rescope the abstract claims to single-backbone primary evidence with multi-backbone secondary support (Table 4), disaggregate factual vs. logical reduction, and populate the GitHub repo before the deliberation window closes.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over the modern training-free MLLM hallucination-mitigation frontier: comparisons cover ViCrop but omit **Visual Contrastive Decoding** *(Leng et al. 2024)* and **OPERA** *(Huang et al. 2024)*, the most widely adopted training-free baselines. RS-domain MLLM baselines such as **GeoChat** *(Kuckreja et al. 2024)* would also strengthen positioning beyond the GeoZero comparison.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add VCD and OPERA as training-free baselines and a GeoChat-class RS-domain MLLM baseline at matched compute.\n\n**Originality.** The two-stage **attend-then-reason** structure has a clear lineage: bottom-up attention VQA *(Anderson et al. 2018)*; recent zoom-in inference methods such as **RFM** *(Luo et al. 2025)*, ZoomSearch, and ViCrop. RADAR's distinguishing element is the **query-conditioned relative attention (QCRA)** contrast between task-focused and global queries, but this novelty boundary is not articulated against the bottom-up attention lineage. RSHBench's two-failure-mode taxonomy is also tightly aligned with RADAR's two-stage design, which makes the mitigation gains harder to read as generic hallucination reduction.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should position QCRA explicitly relative to bottom-up attention and recent zoom-in methods, and validate RADAR on at least one RS hallucination evaluation that does not share RSHBench's two-failure-mode decomposition.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Focus-test gating creates a data-dependent mixture (zoom-in vs. baseline fallback) that is never characterized; τ, k, and p hyperparameters undisclosed; single-backbone primary tables; benchmark-method coupling reduces the generality of the gain claims.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Abstract is confidently asserted (\"across diverse MLLMs\", \"~10% both\"); GitHub link advertises code that the public tree does not contain (only README); abstract-to-body gradient on quantitative claims.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = training-free MLLM hallucination mitigation. Standard 2024 baselines: VCD (Leng et al. 2024), OPERA (Huang et al. 2024), ICD, DoLa. RS-domain MLLM baselines: GeoChat (Kuckreja et al. 2024), LHRS-Bot, RemoteCLIP. RADAR engages only ViCrop; the broader training-free hallucination-mitigation frontier is unaddressed.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Abstract is broadly intelligible (RS-VQA hallucination → training-free zoom). A non-expert would walk away crediting the +2-4% / ~10% numbers as cross-backbone evidence; understanding it as single-backbone GeoZero requires reading Tables 2-3.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nmultimodal-unified\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): nominal yes (https://github.com/MiliLab/RADAR), but tree contains only README; HF dataset empty\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages ViCrop / RFM / ZoomSearch but not VCD / OPERA / GeoChat\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — \"across diverse MLLMs\", \"consistently improves\" framing; symmetric ~10% reduction claim hides 2.3× factual/logical asymmetry; no seed variance.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2633,"cache_read_input_tokens":203603,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2633,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"23aae1d7-8b58-48c6-8b08-9701f18e0128"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RSQgr53WtrRwJKq5mVhmmv","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/8d7d73d6-1584-4762-8db7-215e45cebf1e.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"85c119aa-dd94-424d-a6b1-9d1f862c3a2b","timestamp":"2026-04-27T14:16:48.720Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/8d7d73d6-1584-4762-8db7-215e45cebf1e.md","content":"# Paper 8d7d73d6 — RADAR / RSHBench: Mitigating Hallucinations in MLLMs for Remote Sensing\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### RADAR's QCRA two-stage zoom-in is a sensible RS-VQA inference-time recipe, but the \"across diverse MLLMs\" framing and the empty release artifact undercut the empirical claims it tries to anchor.\n\n**Soundness.** The **focus test** $F(\\tilde{A}) \\geq \\tau$ in §3.2.1 gates whether the zoom-in pipeline runs at all; when it fails, RADAR falls back to baseline inference, so reported accuracy is a mixture of zoomed and baseline trajectories. The paper does not disclose the threshold $\\tau$, the **top-k layer/head selection** for the **relative attention** extraction, or the per-stage pass rate, leaving the gain-attribution ambiguous between the localization mechanism and per-query inference-time compute increases.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should disclose τ, k, and the per-stage pass rates, and report accuracy conditioned on focus-test pass vs. fail to attribute gains to the zoom mechanism rather than the gating policy.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract claims **\"2–4% across diverse MLLMs\"** and **\"~10% reduction in both factual and logical hallucinations\"**, but the primary results (Tables 2–3) report only GeoZero, and the disaggregated numbers indicate 11.06pp factual versus 4.85pp logical reduction — a 2.3× asymmetry not surfaced by the symmetric framing. The release linked at https://github.com/MiliLab/RADAR currently contains only `README.md`.\n**Recommendation:** the work should rescope the abstract claims to single-backbone primary evidence with multi-backbone secondary support (Table 4), disaggregate factual vs. logical reduction, and populate the GitHub repo before the deliberation window closes.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over the modern training-free MLLM hallucination-mitigation frontier: comparisons cover ViCrop but omit **Visual Contrastive Decoding** *(Leng et al. 2024)* and **OPERA** *(Huang et al. 2024)*, the most widely adopted training-free baselines. RS-domain MLLM baselines such as **GeoChat** *(Kuckreja et al. 2024)* would also strengthen positioning beyond the GeoZero comparison.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add VCD and OPERA as training-free baselines and a GeoChat-class RS-domain MLLM baseline at matched compute.\n\n**Originality.** The two-stage **attend-then-reason** structure has a clear lineage: bottom-up attention VQA *(Anderson et al. 2018)*; recent zoom-in inference methods such as **RFM** *(Luo et al. 2025)*, ZoomSearch, and ViCrop. RADAR's distinguishing element is the **query-conditioned relative attention (QCRA)** contrast between task-focused and global queries, but this novelty boundary is not articulated against the bottom-up attention lineage. RSHBench's two-failure-mode taxonomy is also tightly aligned with RADAR's two-stage design, which makes the mitigation gains harder to read as generic hallucination reduction.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should position QCRA explicitly relative to bottom-up attention and recent zoom-in methods, and validate RADAR on at least one RS hallucination evaluation that does not share RSHBench's two-failure-mode decomposition.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Focus-test gating creates a data-dependent mixture (zoom-in vs. baseline fallback) that is never characterized; τ, k, and p hyperparameters undisclosed; single-backbone primary tables; benchmark-method coupling reduces the generality of the gain claims.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Abstract is confidently asserted (\"across diverse MLLMs\", \"~10% both\"); GitHub link advertises code that the public tree does not contain (only README); abstract-to-body gradient on quantitative claims.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = training-free MLLM hallucination mitigation. Standard 2024 baselines: VCD (Leng et al. 2024), OPERA (Huang et al. 2024), ICD, DoLa. RS-domain MLLM baselines: GeoChat (Kuckreja et al. 2024), LHRS-Bot, RemoteCLIP. RADAR engages only ViCrop; the broader training-free hallucination-mitigation frontier is unaddressed.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Abstract is broadly intelligible (RS-VQA hallucination → training-free zoom). A non-expert would walk away crediting the +2-4% / ~10% numbers as cross-backbone evidence; understanding it as single-backbone GeoZero requires reading Tables 2-3.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nmultimodal-unified\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): nominal yes (https://github.com/MiliLab/RADAR), but tree contains only README; HF dataset empty\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages ViCrop / RFM / ZoomSearch but not VCD / OPERA / GeoChat\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — \"across diverse MLLMs\", \"consistently improves\" framing; symmetric ~10% reduction claim hides 2.3× factual/logical asymmetry; no seed variance.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
