{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GppmuADy9LwMt148n9vo6s","type":"tool_result","content":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"d2fe9380-8649-4e27-a70b-9357bb154f63","timestamp":"2026-04-27T14:28:36.139Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out","stderr":"\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_017fN7EWP3WpEzAub5Dk3R6D","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CJWMhf3qfBwHSc5CvDqNCG","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/a2225f35-7e0a-4051-9e62-72dd01763783.md","content":"# Paper a2225f35 — Uncovering Context Reliance in Unstructured Knowledge Editing\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### Context Reliance is a real failure mode and the prepend-recovery diagnostic is elegant, but the paper overclaims novelty against CoRE *(Park et al. 2025)*, leans on a toy single-token attention assumption, and does not separate COIN's gains from those of standard prefix-dropout augmentation.\n\n**Soundness.** **Theorem 3.2** derives Context Reliance from gradient dynamics under **Assumption 3.1**, which collapses dense multi-head attention to \"exactly one relevant and one context token\" — a severe abstraction relative to Llama3 / Qwen2.5 attention patterns. The empirical positional-degradation finding (Figure 2) is also potentially a property of unedited autoregressive models reading the same text, not an editing-induced pathology; this is not isolated by an **unedited-model baseline** experiment.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should report Theorem 3.2 results under at least one relaxation of Assumption 3.1 (e.g., distributed-attention setting), and add an unedited-model baseline that reads the AKEW text in-context to test whether positional degradation is editing-specific or autoregressive-general.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract's headline gain is **\"23.6%\"** while the introduction reports **\"25.6%\"** — an internal discrepancy. The framing of Context Reliance as \"uncovered\" overstates novelty against Park et al. 2025 CoRE *(arXiv:2505.23026)*, which already identified preceding-context fragility in knowledge editing.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should reconcile the 23.6% / 25.6% discrepancy, cite and explicitly differentiate from CoRE, and reframe as \"diagnosing Context Reliance specifically in the NTP paradigm\" rather than a general discovery.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence to attribute COIN's gains to its **Context Alignment Loss** versus simpler regularization: a **prefix-truncation data augmentation** baseline (NTP fine-tuning with randomly truncated preceding context) is the natural control and is absent. Comparison to recent unstructured-editing baselines such as **UnKE** *(Deng et al. 2024)* and **AnyEdit** *(Jiang et al. 2025)* is reportedly included on UnKEBench, but the headline gain over MEMIT-class **locate-and-edit** *(Meng et al. 2022)* methods on counterfactual edits — the hardest case — is not surfaced.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a prefix-truncation augmentation baseline at matched compute, and report counterfactual-edit accuracy against MEMIT and ROME on AKEW.\n\n**Originality.** The Context Reliance phenomenon is a specific instance of **prefix-overfitting / shortcut learning** in causal LMs, well-documented under names like the **reversal curse** *(Berglund et al. 2023)* and **\"Lost in the Middle\"** *(Liu et al. 2024)* positional bias. The paper's genuine contributions are (a) NTP-paradigm-specific diagnosis with the prepend-recovery experiment and (b) the COIN loss formulation. The conceptual delta over CoRE is the NTP-specific theoretical grounding, which is real but narrower than the title suggests.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should retitle the contribution as \"NTP-specific Context Reliance and COIN mitigation\" and explicitly position the phenomenon within the prefix-overfitting / reversal-curse / Lost-in-the-Middle lineage.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Theorem 3.2 hinges on Assumption 3.1 single-token attention — a toy setting; positional degradation in Fig 2 may be autoregressive-general not editing-specific; no unedited-baseline isolation.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Diagnostic via prepend-recovery (Fig 3) is elegant; abstract/intro 23.6% vs 25.6% discrepancy is a clarity defect; \"uncovering\" framing is unhedged.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = unstructured knowledge editing. Standard precedents: UnKE (Deng 2024), AnyEdit (Jiang 2025), MEMIT (Meng 2022), ROME, CoRE (Park 2025). Broader phenomenon precedents: reversal curse (Berglund 2023), Lost in the Middle (Liu 2024). Paper engages UnKE / AnyEdit but missing CoRE direct precedent.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Knowledge editing fails when context is removed\" framing is intuitive; non-expert would credit the +23.6% as a method-specific gain rather than a regularization-equivalent one.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nnone — knowledge editing is adjacent to alignment but not on the trending list.\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced; theory in §3.2 is short relative to empirical sections\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no (github_repo_url null)\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages UnKE / AnyEdit, missing CoRE / reversal-curse / Lost-in-the-Middle as positioning anchors\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — abstract uses unhedged \"outperforms strong baselines by 23.6%\" and \"uncovers\" framing; mixed against the CoRE prior art and the 25.6% intro figure.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2463,"cache_read_input_tokens":331179,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2463,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":69,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"d2caeb80-a3af-498e-9b9d-d8e58bfc7a3c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CJWMhf3qfBwHSc5CvDqNCG","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/a2225f35-7e0a-4051-9e62-72dd01763783.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"482b1f7f-e048-421c-bcf3-fc9d6a69aad5","timestamp":"2026-04-27T14:29:09.799Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/a2225f35-7e0a-4051-9e62-72dd01763783.md","content":"# Paper a2225f35 — Uncovering Context Reliance in Unstructured Knowledge Editing\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### Context Reliance is a real failure mode and the prepend-recovery diagnostic is elegant, but the paper overclaims novelty against CoRE *(Park et al. 2025)*, leans on a toy single-token attention assumption, and does not separate COIN's gains from those of standard prefix-dropout augmentation.\n\n**Soundness.** **Theorem 3.2** derives Context Reliance from gradient dynamics under **Assumption 3.1**, which collapses dense multi-head attention to \"exactly one relevant and one context token\" — a severe abstraction relative to Llama3 / Qwen2.5 attention patterns. The empirical positional-degradation finding (Figure 2) is also potentially a property of unedited autoregressive models reading the same text, not an editing-induced pathology; this is not isolated by an **unedited-model baseline** experiment.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should report Theorem 3.2 results under at least one relaxation of Assumption 3.1 (e.g., distributed-attention setting), and add an unedited-model baseline that reads the AKEW text in-context to test whether positional degradation is editing-specific or autoregressive-general.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract's headline gain is **\"23.6%\"** while the introduction reports **\"25.6%\"** — an internal discrepancy. The framing of Context Reliance as \"uncovered\" overstates novelty against Park et al. 2025 CoRE *(arXiv:2505.23026)*, which already identified preceding-context fragility in knowledge editing.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should reconcile the 23.6% / 25.6% discrepancy, cite and explicitly differentiate from CoRE, and reframe as \"diagnosing Context Reliance specifically in the NTP paradigm\" rather than a general discovery.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence to attribute COIN's gains to its **Context Alignment Loss** versus simpler regularization: a **prefix-truncation data augmentation** baseline (NTP fine-tuning with randomly truncated preceding context) is the natural control and is absent. Comparison to recent unstructured-editing baselines such as **UnKE** *(Deng et al. 2024)* and **AnyEdit** *(Jiang et al. 2025)* is reportedly included on UnKEBench, but the headline gain over MEMIT-class **locate-and-edit** *(Meng et al. 2022)* methods on counterfactual edits — the hardest case — is not surfaced.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a prefix-truncation augmentation baseline at matched compute, and report counterfactual-edit accuracy against MEMIT and ROME on AKEW.\n\n**Originality.** The Context Reliance phenomenon is a specific instance of **prefix-overfitting / shortcut learning** in causal LMs, well-documented under names like the **reversal curse** *(Berglund et al. 2023)* and **\"Lost in the Middle\"** *(Liu et al. 2024)* positional bias. The paper's genuine contributions are (a) NTP-paradigm-specific diagnosis with the prepend-recovery experiment and (b) the COIN loss formulation. The conceptual delta over CoRE is the NTP-specific theoretical grounding, which is real but narrower than the title suggests.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should retitle the contribution as \"NTP-specific Context Reliance and COIN mitigation\" and explicitly position the phenomenon within the prefix-overfitting / reversal-curse / Lost-in-the-Middle lineage.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Theorem 3.2 hinges on Assumption 3.1 single-token attention — a toy setting; positional degradation in Fig 2 may be autoregressive-general not editing-specific; no unedited-baseline isolation.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Diagnostic via prepend-recovery (Fig 3) is elegant; abstract/intro 23.6% vs 25.6% discrepancy is a clarity defect; \"uncovering\" framing is unhedged.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = unstructured knowledge editing. Standard precedents: UnKE (Deng 2024), AnyEdit (Jiang 2025), MEMIT (Meng 2022), ROME, CoRE (Park 2025). Broader phenomenon precedents: reversal curse (Berglund 2023), Lost in the Middle (Liu 2024). Paper engages UnKE / AnyEdit but missing CoRE direct precedent.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Knowledge editing fails when context is removed\" framing is intuitive; non-expert would credit the +23.6% as a method-specific gain rather than a regularization-equivalent one.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nnone — knowledge editing is adjacent to alignment but not on the trending list.\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced; theory in §3.2 is short relative to empirical sections\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no (github_repo_url null)\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages UnKE / AnyEdit, missing CoRE / reversal-curse / Lost-in-the-Middle as positioning anchors\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — abstract uses unhedged \"outperforms strong baselines by 23.6%\" and \"uncovers\" framing; mixed against the CoRE prior art and the 25.6% intro figure.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
