{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015tLYE3ULUsMrMhxSd2X4J7","type":"tool_result","content":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"2f17c7d1-98be-4c24-879a-892faaa31466","timestamp":"2026-04-27T14:31:02.555Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"M\tagent_configs/qwerty81/agent.log\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.err\nM\tagent_configs/qwerty81/cluster.9379790.out","stderr":"\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/agent_configs/qwerty81","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01EPf6VF7TbF5gTpVjtc9NV7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0141wGfbRVv3vQv3NjvnvfNV","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/d263efbe-b41a-4d55-932c-6ea58c4c9e32.md","content":"# Paper d263efbe — Quantifying Frontier LLM Capabilities for Container Sandbox Escape (SandboxEscapeBench)\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### SandboxEscapeBench is a methodologically careful evaluation of LLM container-escape capability, with the sandbox-in-sandbox harness and shortcut prevention as its strongest contribution; however, the absence of non-LLM null baselines and the unexplained GPT-5.2 regression weaken the headline framing of monotonic frontier capability growth.\n\n**Soundness.** Tables 1–2 report only LLM-vs-LLM comparisons; Difficulty-1 / Difficulty-2 misconfiguration scenarios (exposed Docker sockets, privileged containers, writable host mounts) are detectable by **category-aware shell scripts** with no language-model involvement, leaving the LLM-specific contribution unisolated. The **GPT-5.2 regression** (0.27 [0.19, 0.37] vs. GPT-5 at 0.50 [0.40, 0.60], ~47% relative drop with non-overlapping CIs) is acknowledged but unattributed, with two opposite-implication candidate explanations (safety-alignment refusal vs. capability artifact).\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add a non-LLM scripted-agent null baseline (category-aware shell heuristics) at each difficulty tier, and report disengagement-rate and false-success-rate breakdowns by model version to disambiguate the GPT-5.2 regression.\n\n**Presentation.** The abstract claims **\"LLMs are able to identify and exploit\"** seeded vulnerabilities, but the relative rate compared to scripted heuristics is not surfaced. **Difficulty ratings (1–5)** are based on a single expert's estimate, and the private test set limits independent reproducibility despite the public release of 18 scenarios.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should cross-validate difficulty ratings with ≥3 independent security-professional ratings, and document the released-vs-private split explicitly.\n\n**Significance.** The methodology lacks evidence for SoTA over the modern AI-cybersecurity-benchmark frontier: comparisons should engage **Cybench** *(Zhang et al. 2024)*, **InterCode-CTF** *(Yang et al. 2023)*, and **EnIGMA** *(Abramovich et al. 2024)* to position container-escape as a distinct sub-task. Concurrent **SandboxBench** *(2025)* should also be cited and differentiated. Without this, the contribution risks reading as a parallel evaluation rather than a frontier advance.\n**Recommendation:** the work should add a comparative analysis against Cybench / InterCode-CTF / EnIGMA on the container-escape subset, and engage SandboxBench as concurrent prior art.\n\n**Originality.** The empirical extension from generic CVE exploitation *(Fang et al. 2024)* to container-escape CVEs is incremental; the genuinely novel contributions are the **sandbox-in-sandbox harness** and the **shortcut-prevention protocol** (Appendix C, four unintended escape paths identified during development). Both are reusable AI-safety evaluation engineering rather than capability discoveries, which is the clearest framing of the paper's contribution.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should retitle the contribution as \"evaluation engineering for container-escape CTFs\" with capability measurement as a downstream consequence, foregrounding the methodological reusability over the capability-trajectory narrative.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** No null/scripted baselines; difficulty ratings from single expert; GPT-5.2 regression unexplained; private test set + 18 public scenarios mixed reproducibility.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Strong narrative on AI safety evaluation; \"frontier capability growth\" framing tension with GPT-5.2 regression in own data.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = AI-agent cybersecurity evaluation. Standard precedents: Cybench (Zhang 2024), InterCode-CTF (Yang 2023), EnIGMA (Abramovich 2024), Fang et al. 2024 one-day CVE; concurrent: SandboxBench 2025. Paper engages Fang et al. only.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Container-escape framing is intuitive for safety researchers; non-expert would credit \"LLMs can escape sandboxes\" without realizing the seeded-vulnerabilities scope.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai — frontier-model capability evaluation under adversarial agentic conditions\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced; Appendix C shortcut-prevention is detailed\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/UKGovernmentBEIS/sandbox_escape_bench, plus Inspect AI ecosystem)\n- Citation freshness: partial — engages Fang et al. 2024 but not Cybench / InterCode-CTF / EnIGMA / SandboxBench\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — abstract is unhedged on \"LLMs are able to identify and exploit\"; Section 6 honestly notes \"no novel vulnerabilities discovered\"; GPT-5.2 regression is acknowledged but not interpreted.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2793,"cache_read_input_tokens":350107,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2793,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":69,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80053081-ac83-483f-ab5a-50ade4c3171d","uuid":"11a384b2-d737-4407-82c3-bb6995610c63"}
